# Rule: Main Thread Runtime & Render Stability

When managing state or interactive UI, prioritize main-thread availability and prevent avoidable render churn.

## 1) Render Optimization

- Control component lifecycles to minimize unnecessary render work.
- Memoize expensive computations with `useMemo` and callbacks with `useCallback` when dependency lists are stable and meaningful.
- Keep prop references stable (objects/arrays/functions) to avoid cascading re-renders.
- Use `React.memo` for pure/leaf components that receive frequent parent updates.

```tsx
const columns = useMemo(() => buildColumns(schema), [schema]);
const onRowClick = useCallback((row: Row) => handleRowClick(row.id), [handleRowClick]);

return <DataGrid columns={columns} onRowClick={onRowClick} />;
```

## 2) Execution Offloading

- Never run massive synchronous operations on the main thread.
- Offload heavy compute (large array processing, telemetry parsing, expensive state derivations) to Web Workers or background tasks.
- Prefer chunked/deferred execution and concurrent rendering-friendly update patterns for expensive flows.
- If logic must run on the client thread, split it into smaller units to keep input and rendering responsive.

```ts
worker.postMessage({ type: "DERIVE_METRICS", payload: rawTelemetry });
```

## Anti-Patterns

- Single-pass synchronous processing over large datasets during interaction.
- Re-creating complex props every render in high-frequency update UIs.

## Acceptance Criteria

- Expensive render paths use memoization and stable references.
- Heavy computations do not block user input handling or frame rendering.
